Basics Of ML
Question and their answer to cover the basics of ML

## 1. How would you define Machine Learning?

ğŸ‘‰ Machine Learning is the field of study that gives computers the ability to learn from data and improve performance on a task without being explicitly programmed.

## 2. Can you name four types of problems where it shines?

Spam filtering

Image recognition (e.g., face detection)

Speech recognition (e.g., Siri, Alexa)

Recommendation systems (e.g., Netflix, Amazon)

## 3. What is a labeled training set?

ğŸ‘‰ A dataset where each input example is paired with the correct output (label).
Example: emails (input) + spam/ham (label).

## 4. What are the two most common supervised tasks?

Classification (predicting categories â†’ spam or not spam)

Regression (predicting values â†’ house prices)

## 5. Can you name four common unsupervised tasks?

Clustering (e.g., customer segmentation)

Dimensionality reduction (e.g., PCA)

Anomaly detection (e.g., fraud detection)

Association rule learning (e.g., â€œpeople who buy X also buy Yâ€)

## 6. What type of ML algorithm would you use to allow a robot to walk in various unknown terrains?

ğŸ‘‰ Reinforcement Learning (agent learns by trial and error with rewards/penalties).

## 7. What type of algorithm would you use to segment your customers into multiple groups?

ğŸ‘‰ Clustering (unsupervised learning).

## 8. Would you frame spam detection as supervised or unsupervised?

ğŸ‘‰ Supervised learning (emails labeled as spam/ham).

## 9. What is an online learning system?

ğŸ‘‰ A system that learns incrementally as new data arrives, instead of retraining from scratch.

## 10. What is out-of-core learning?

ğŸ‘‰ Training on datasets too large to fit in memory, by streaming data in mini-batches from disk.

## 11. What type of algorithm relies on a similarity measure to make predictions?

ğŸ‘‰ Instance-based learning (e.g., k-Nearest Neighbors).

## 12. Difference between model parameter and hyperparameter?

Parameter: learned by the algorithm during training (e.g., weights in linear regression).

Hyperparameter: set before training, controls learning (e.g., learning rate, k in kNN).

## 13. What do model-based learning algorithms search for?

ğŸ‘‰ They search for the best parameters that minimize a cost function.
Most common strategy â†’ Gradient Descent.
Predictions â†’ Use the learned function (hypothesis) to make predictions on new data.

## 14. Can you name four main challenges in ML?

Insufficient data

Poor quality data (noise, missing values)

Overfitting (model too complex)

Underfitting (model too simple)

## 15. If your model performs great on training data but poorly on new instances, what is happening?

ğŸ‘‰ Overfitting.
âœ… Solutions:

Get more training data

Reduce model complexity / add regularization

Clean the training data

## 16. What is a test set, and why use it?

ğŸ‘‰ A dataset kept aside to evaluate generalization of the final trained model.
It simulates performance on unseen data.

## 17. What is the purpose of a validation set?

ğŸ‘‰ Used to tune hyperparameters and select the best model, without touching the test set.

## 18. What is the train-dev set, when do you need it, and how do you use it?

ğŸ‘‰ Proposed by Andrew Ng for data mismatch problems.

Itâ€™s a subset of the training data.

Used to check if the model overfits the training data (vs. mismatch with validation/test).

Helps diagnose whether poor validation results come from overfitting or data mismatch.

## 19. What can go wrong if you tune hyperparameters using the test set?

ğŸ‘‰ You would leak information from the test set â†’ model indirectly fits the test set â†’ evaluation becomes biased.
Result: Test performance is overly optimistic, and you canâ€™t trust it anymore.
